  "prompt": "Where can I study at Stanford?",
  "response": "Stanford University offers a variety of study spaces tailored to different preferences and needs. Here are some popular options:\n\n1. **Green Library**: The main library on campus, Green Library offers both quiet and collaborative study spaces. It also has a variety of resources including books, journals, and digital materials.\n\n2. **Lathrop Library**: Known for its technology resources, Lathrop Library provides study spaces, computer stations, and group study rooms.\n\n3. **Engineering Quad**: Many buildings in the Engineering Quad have study spaces, including the Huang Engineering Center, which has lounges and quiet areas.\n\n4. **Hass Center**: The Haas Center for Public Service has study spaces available for students engaged in public service activities.\n\n5. **School of Medicine**: The Li Ka Shing Learning and Knowledge Center offers study spaces for medical students, including quiet rooms and group study areas.\n\n6. **Graduate Student Center (GSC)**: Located in the Old Union, the GSC provides study spaces and resources geared towards graduate students.\n\n7. **Residential Halls**: Most residential halls have common areas and lounges where students can study.\n\n8. **Outdoor Spaces**: Stanford\u2019s campus has beautiful outdoor areas like Meyer Green, the Main Quad, and various courtyards that can be great for studying when the weather is nice.\n\n9. **Caf\u00e9s and Dining Areas**: Places like Coupa Caf\u00e9, Starbucks, and other dining spots on campus can also serve as good study environments.\n\n10. **Department-specific Libraries**: Many departments have their own libraries or study spaces, such as the Stanford Law Library or the Business Library at the Graduate School of Business.\n\nIt\u2019s always a good idea to explore different locations to find the study environment that suits you best.",
